---
import Base from '~/layouts/Base.astro';
---

<Base
  title="About — PGConf Poland 2026"
  description="PGConf Poland 2026 brings the PostgreSQL community to Gdańsk for a single-day, single-track conference of talks, workshops, and conversation."
>
  <section class="section section--hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">About the conference</p>
      <h1 class="page-title">A new chapter for PostgreSQL in Poland.</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        PGConf Poland 2026 is the inaugural Polish edition of the PostgreSQL Europe conference series — a
        single day in Gdańsk dedicated to the database that quietly powers an unreasonable share of the
        modern internet. One track, one room, sixty seats, and the people who actually run, build and
        teach Postgres for a living.
      </p>
      <span class="rule rule--gold" aria-hidden="true"></span>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container grid grid--two">
      <div>
        <h2 class="section-title">Our mission</h2>
        <p>
          PostgreSQL has grown from a research project into a load-bearing piece of public and private
          infrastructure across Europe. PGConf Poland exists to give the people responsible for that work
          — operators, developers, data engineers, and the leaders who fund them — a deliberately small,
          high-signal day to compare notes, learn what is changing in the project, and meet the
          contributors behind the release notes.
        </p>
        <p>
          We organise around three commitments: independent, community-led programming; honest technical
          content over marketing; and a welcoming environment governed by the PostgreSQL Europe Code of
          Conduct.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="card card--gold">
        <h3 class="card-title">At a glance</h3>
        <dl class="meta">
          <div><dt>Date</dt><dd>24 November 2026</dd></div>
          <div><dt>City</dt><dd>Gdańsk, Poland</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Venue</dt><dd>ARCHE Dwór Uphagena</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Format</dt><dd>Single day, single track</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Capacity</dt><dd>60 attendees</dd></div>
          <div><dt>Language</dt><dd>English</dd></div>
        </dl>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">A short history</h2>
      <span class="rule rule--gold rule--sm" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      <div class="grid grid--two">
        <p>
          PostgreSQL Europe has been running national and regional events since 2008 — PGConf.EU, PGDay
          Paris, Nordic PGDay, PGDay UK, PGDay Lowlands and others. Each new edition follows the same
          template the community has refined for nearly two decades: contributor-driven, vendor-neutral,
          and rooted in a host city with a strong technical scene.
        </p>
        <p>
          2026 is the first time the series formally lands in Poland. Polish engineers have been a steady
          presence at European Postgres events for years; bringing the conference home was a question of
          when, not whether. We chose Gdańsk for its accessibility, its Hanseatic and maritime history,
          and a venue inside the historic Dwór Uphagena complex that suits the intimate scale we want for
          a first edition.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Who it is for</h2>
      <span class="rule rule--gold rule--sm" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      <ul class="audience">
        <li>
          <h3>Database administrators</h3>
          <p>
            Production operators of PostgreSQL — replication, backups, upgrades, observability,
            performance triage and the everyday craft of keeping clusters healthy at scale.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <h3>Application developers</h3>
          <p>
            Engineers who write the queries, design the schemas and pick the extensions. SQL patterns,
            JSONB, full-text search, partitioning, logical replication and the parts of Postgres that
            replace a second service.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <h3>Data engineers and analysts</h3>
          <p>
            People moving data into, through and out of Postgres. Analytical workloads, columnar
            extensions, streaming ingest, FDWs, CDC and the boundary with the warehouse.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <h3>Technical decision-makers</h3>
          <p>
            CTOs, architects and engineering managers evaluating Postgres for new platforms or planning a
            migration off a proprietary stack. A day among practitioners is a fast way to calibrate.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">The format</h2>
      <span class="rule rule--gold rule--sm" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      <ol class="day">
        <li>
          <span class="day__time">08:30 — 09:15</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Registration and morning coffee</h3>
            <p>Foyer Sali Miś — pick up your badge, lanyard and printed schedule.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="day__time">09:15 — 12:30</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Morning talks</h3>
            <p>Single track in Sala Bastion Miś with a short break between sessions.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="day__time">12:30 — 13:45</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Networking lunch</h3>
            <p>Buffet served in Restauracja Stara Kuchnia, with sponsor tables open in Spiżarnia.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="day__time">13:45 — 17:30</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Afternoon talks and workshop</h3>
            <p>
              Main-track sessions continue in Sala Bastion Miś; a parallel hands-on workshop runs in
              Sala "U Profesora B" with limited seats.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="day__time">17:30 — 18:00</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Closing remarks and lightning talks</h3>
            <p>Five-minute slots, signed up on the day.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <span class="day__time">18:30 onwards</span>
          <div>
            <h3>Evening social</h3>
            <p>Casual reception in the Old Town. Details and a walking route in your welcome pack.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p class="footnote">
        Times are indicative — the final running order is published when the Call for Papers closes.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container cta">
      <h2 class="section-title">Who is putting this on</h2>
      <span class="rule rule--gold rule--sm" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      <p>
        PGConf Poland 2026 is produced by the volunteer organising and programme committees, under the
        umbrella of PostgreSQL Europe. Meet the people behind it on the
        <a href="/organisation" class="link-arrow">Organisation page<span aria-hidden="true">&nbsp;→</span></a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>

<style>
  .section {
    padding-block: clamp(3.5rem, 7vw, 6rem);
  }
  .section--alt {
    background: var(--color-bg-elev);
    border-block: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }
  .section--hero {
    padding-block: clamp(5rem, 10vw, 8rem) clamp(2.5rem, 5vw, 4rem);
  }
  .container {
    max-width: 72rem;
    margin-inline: auto;
    padding-inline: clamp(1.25rem, 4vw, 2.5rem);
  }
  .eyebrow {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-gold);
    margin: 0 0 1.25rem;
  }
  .page-title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4.25rem);
    line-height: 1.05;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
    max-width: 22ch;
  }
  .lede {
    font-size: clamp(1.075rem, 1.6vw, 1.25rem);
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--color-fg-muted);
    max-width: 60ch;
    margin: 0 0 2rem;
  }
  .section-title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: clamp(1.75rem, 3vw, 2.5rem);
    letter-spacing: -0.005em;
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
  }
  .rule {
    display: block;
    height: 1px;
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--color-gold), transparent);
    margin: 0.25rem 0 2rem;
  }
  .rule--gold {
    width: 8rem;
    background: linear-gradient(90deg, var(--color-gold), var(--color-gold-warm), transparent);
    height: 2px;
  }
  .rule--sm {
    width: 4rem;
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }
  .grid {
    display: grid;
    gap: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 3.5rem);
  }
  .grid--two {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
  @media (min-width: 56rem) {
    .grid--two {
      grid-template-columns: 1.4fr 1fr;
      align-items: start;
    }
  }
  p {
    color: var(--color-fg-muted);
    line-height: 1.65;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    max-width: 62ch;
  }
  .card {
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    background: var(--color-bg-elev);
    padding: 1.75rem 1.75rem 1.5rem;
    position: relative;
  }
  .card--gold::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    border-top: 2px solid var(--color-gold);
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  .card-title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    color: var(--color-fg);
  }
  .meta {
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.65rem;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .meta > div {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 7rem 1fr;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }
  .meta dt {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--color-gold);
    padding-top: 0.15rem;
  }
  .meta dd {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--color-fg);
  }
  .audience {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 1.75rem;
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
  }
  @media (min-width: 48rem) {
    .audience {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    }
  }
  .audience li {
    border-left: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
  }
  .audience h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
    color: var(--color-fg);
  }
  .audience p {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .day {
    list-style: none;
    counter-reset: step;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
    display: grid;
    gap: 1.25rem;
    max-width: 56rem;
  }
  .day li {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 0.35rem;
    padding: 1.25rem 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }
  @media (min-width: 40rem) {
    .day li {
      grid-template-columns: 11rem 1fr;
      gap: 1.5rem;
      align-items: baseline;
    }
  }
  .day li:last-child {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }
  .day__time {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--color-gold);
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }
  .day h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    color: var(--color-fg);
    margin: 0 0 0.25rem;
  }
  .day p {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    margin: 0;
  }
  .footnote {
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    color: var(--color-fg-muted);
    margin-top: 1.25rem;
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .cta {
    text-align: left;
    max-width: 48rem;
  }
  .link-arrow {
    color: var(--color-gold);
    text-decoration: none;
    border-bottom: 1px solid color-mix(in oklab, var(--color-gold) 35%, transparent);
    transition: border-color 160ms ease;
  }
  .link-arrow:hover {
    border-bottom-color: var(--color-gold);
  }
</style>
